segments.text: You're heading for the lighthouse and he wanted you to hit it right on the button.
He didn't want you to be a mile off this way or that way.
And he was just, everything was the same way.
I mean, if you had a bomb wing and you're supposed to be able to load the bombs and be ready to go in 30 minutes, why, were you supposed to practice enough that you'd make it in 30 minutes?
And this was a... A perfectionist.
A perfectionist, right.
That's the word you think that would... Obviously, that's right.
And still he had the human touch that people liked to work for him.
And... And he drove fast cars.
I mean, he...
And one of his hobbies was his turbocharged automobiles.
And he'd work on them himself.
So when I was down at Homestead, he called me up one day and wanted me to go up to some outfit in West Palm Beach to look at a supercharger that he had.
Some outfit was working up there, some machine shop.
And it was a machine shop made up of retired people.
They didn't hire anything but retired people, machinists from Detroit and what have you.
They were machinists that just did part time work, but they were so good that
The guy that worked in the morning could continue the job of the guy in the afternoon.
And they made a real good supercharger so I told him what they cost and what I thought of the plant and he took it from there.
Good man to work for.
Oh yeah, he's a real good man to work for.
How's his health right now?
Oh I think he's pretty good.
How old is he?
He's younger than I am.
I met him by LeMay.
He's older than you are.
Is he?
Yeah.
He always told you older than everybody else.
Seventy-four?
I think he's seventy.
Yeah, I think he's seventy-four now.
That's what I told him in February.
I think that's how old he is.
It was right after your command with the 379th that you were promoted to Brigadier General.
Yeah, well see, as a result of, I mean, actually what we did in 379th is why he promoted me to become the Air Division Commander at Homestead.
Then I just took over from previous commander who was transferred out.
So, at Homestead, how many wing commanders did you have?
Well, you had two wing commanders and an air base group commander.
Okay, so you had three and then you had a brigadier general in charge of those three who was in charge of the entire air division.
Yeah, then you had three colonels commanding one air base group and two wing commanders.
19th Bomb Wing, 379th Bomb Wing, and the Air Base Group.
In other words, so you went from leading about 1,800 men to leading 6,500 men.
Yeah, probably 30, probably pretty close, about 5,000.
Now you remained a colonel from, I think, 1943 to 1957.
Is that right?
Were you getting frustrated?
Well, that's the reason I said I was going to go to my master's degree.
When I commanded the 315, way back in 48, I was recommended for promotion at that time.
And I was recommended for promotion when I commanded the security service.
Well, I just wasn't selected at the time.
So I figured that
If the Air Force didn't want to promote me, I just didn't want to be dead wood around.
How many times can you be passed over?
Well, you're not passed over.
Okay, well, what's the difference here?
I mean, a man who now is staying at the same rank for 14 years, I mean, how do they,
I know that sometimes they ease people out of this, or they force retirement, don't they?
How does this work?
Well, see, if you, see I was promoted to permanent colonel, and that automatically grants you 30 years service.
Oh, it does?
Oh, I didn't know that.
Oh, I see.
So if you are promoted to lieutenant colonel, then that automatically grants you 28 years service.
I see.
And then if you don't make lieutenant colonel, then there's a period, I think, 18 years or something of this sort.
And you have to do a lot of string pulling to get to stay on active duty for 20 years in order to be able to retire.
And see, when I was selected for permanent colonel in whatever it is, 46, 48,
Well, then that automatically guaranteed me until 1963.
But you could have retired as early as 1953 with no pay.
Yeah, yeah.
And then if you are selected for a permanent BG, a permanent major channel,
Why didn't you get to stay on for 35 years service?
And so that's the reason that I had to retire in 1963.
So I got promoted to permanent colonel, but not to a permanent BG.
OK. Now let's go back to Homestead, Florida.
OK. For two years there, you were the commander of the Air Division.
How did this differ from your command as a wing commander?
Well, it's more of an administrative job.
More coordination.
A wing commander is more of a flying job.
You're in the day-to-day operations of scheduling, watching airplanes, briefing pilots, and things of this sort.

Your Air Division is a job of checking on each wing to be sure that they're doing their job and checking on the Air Base Group to be sure that they're supporting the wings in the areas that they're supposed to.
And then your Air Division and the Bay Air Base Group are more into the
community functions.
Your flying wing commanders do very little of making speeches to the Rotary Club and things of this sort.
Sure, and so now you got to use some of that personnel development that you received at the Air War College, going out and meeting the Chamber of Commerce and things like that.
Did you give a lot of speeches during this time?
Oh yeah, well you made
Well, not a lot.

A lot of times you just go down and have a cup of coffee with the mayor and have him out or you invite a group of the top civilian personnel, people, the president of the bank and out for lunch and give them a tour of the base.
and tell them how much money we were spending in their community.
Oh, make them feel good.
Tell them how important the Air Force is to their community.
And this type of thing.
And how did you get along with the mayors, and how did you get along with them?
Oh, you get along with them normally real good.
You have no...
I don't know of any...
any problem I had with any mayor, including the mayor of Misawa, Japan, and the governor of the prefecture.
It's the same type of community relations type of thing.

When I was in, speaking of this community relations stuff, I was in the United States Navy, and I was just an enlisted man, but I often found that there was a negative community feeling toward the Navy men, the sailors in the particular towns that I was at.
I would imagine that in Homestead some of your airmen felt the same way.
How did you cope with a problem like that?
Well, I don't remember of any instances where you had any problem.
I think the only problem you have is where your airmen start picking up VD at a certain location and you put it off limits and then everything gets in an uproar when you put some bar off limits.
And that's where you run into, I guess you do your best
persuasive act to get the mayor to clean up the place.
But I don't think we really had the same problems as they had around Fort Benning at one time where we had almost open warfare between the civilian and the military.
I can't remember the town that was in Bob.
But I think if you visit these people or the base commander visits these people once a week, once every two weeks, and you keep everybody informed as to what's going on.
Normally your problems are

or lack of communications, like where they think the military is excluding them and they're not a part of the, because they're looking for the dollars and the number of people that are spending money downtown and who are renting their houses and all this type of thing.
It really didn't
didn't come up.
I don't think we had any problem at all in Florida.
In fact, I didn't ever have too much of a problem anywhere with the civilian.
But as long as you keep them informed as to what's going on and why you have to restrict sometimes all your airmen and your officers to base and
and things of this sort except those that are married or living off base.
You normally have to keep them informed of what's going on and they accept that but it's only when you don't keep them informed as to what's going on.
At this time you must have had some black airmen under your command and here you are in a
pretty much of a segregated state.
Did you have any race problems in Homestead, Florida?
I never had any race problems at any base I had.
That's good.
Because I didn't create a problem.
I just think that the problems that are created by your black personnel is
is one where you start talking about a problem.
And the only area that really came to my attention was when I was stationed in Misawa some time later.
But there you had lots of quarters and the, an airfoil white guy was living there and
colored moving in next door.
Well, if they wanted to move, I said, well, you can move.
You can move wherever you want to.
I mean, here's the other quarters.
You just select them.
And if you want to pay for you and you just want to move, well, just move.
And I said, it's all right with me.
So I didn't restrict them and say, you have to sit there and live right next door to a colored person if they didn't want to live there.
as long as it didn't cost me anything, as long as it didn't cost the government anything.
And the only other item is the colored airmen in barracks would always, every time a white guy would move out, the colored guy would move in.
So that you get all the colored and one in the barracks, and that's a dangerous situation.
So it wasn't ever too much,
these guys with all the congregations in one barracks, I would just disperse them.
And I treated all of them just exactly alike.
I mean, the crew chief, if he had the best flying record of his airplane, he was the number one crew chief, and he got promoted first.
I think as long as you treat them exactly like you treat everybody else,
and you brag on them like you brag on everybody else, I don't think you have any problem.
When I was stationed up in Missoula, I had a colored pilot who was my personal pilot.
He was your personal pilot?
Yeah, I mean, who flew me back and forth to wherever I had to go to a meeting.
And he was good, so as far as I was concerned, it didn't make any difference what color he was, as long as he was good and I felt safe by him.
And when our daughters came back from Stevens and they would land on top of Chicago, he'd go down and pick them up.
And they knew who he was and so we had no problem.
So he was top dog as far as everyone.
So as far as you, if you treat everybody the same, you have no problem.
It's where you start
not treating them different, not promoting them the same, if they were just as good, why you have no problem.
Did you have any, while you were the commander at Homestead, did you, what kind of relations did you have with other commands in the south?
Did you try to cooperate with other commanders and did you fly missions with them or did you have any large scale missions that you went out on?
Well, the only missions that you had were psych missions.
As a wing commander you were just as competitive with the other wings as you are in a football game.
You have a, he had a, General May had an annual bombing competition.
Oh really?
Your wing was, you prepped that just like you did to peak your football team.
He had annual bombing from base, from one SAC base against another SAC base or one wing?
One wing against another wing.
Within your base?
No, no.
No, it was SAC-wide.
Oh, SAC-wide.
Yeah, so you sent, each wing was permitted to send two crews.
And you had a bombing competition, navigation and bombing competition.
And then you just got eliminated on what your bombing score was.
At this time, late 1950s, 1957, 1958,
How many wings were there in SAC?
Do you remember?
Do you have any idea?
I have no idea.

But you're... No, he would have a commanders conference and he'd have all his wing commanders and his division commanders in and they'd meet at one of the bases such as Plattsburgh up in New England and
And you'd play golf, get to know the, play golf and have briefings as to what was going on.
And get all those bank commanders together and get them fighting each other about who was best.
And I mean, that's the way to get things going, you know, is competition.
They loved to put people in situations where they were competing.
Oh, yeah.
Competing, oh yeah.
Who's the best?
But... No, in fact, you had very good relations with the other wing commanders, mostly, and division commanders.
Most of it was a competitive situation.
And who was best and...
He kept me pretty well informed as to what the score was.
Why did he get rid of you?
Why did Curtis LeMay send you to Japan?
Well, some stupid guy, some stupid brigadier general over in Japan had a heart attack.
And I was picked up and moved to Japan overnight just about.
Really?
Yeah.
Well he was the chief of the Air Force section, MAG, who was really an aide to the chief of staff of the Air Defense Force of Japan, Japan Air Force.
And he had a heart attack and they had to pick a general officer right quick and
and said, went over, and I got the job.
I don't know why.
You just get a telegram saying, get prepared.
So basically then, you were a senior advisor to the chief of staff, the Air Force chief of staff in Japan.
You were basically his deputy then?
Or exactly what were your functions?
What does it mean to be an advisor?
You were second in command then?
No, what you were doing, you were, see we provided the Japanese with the air defense command equipment and we provided them with the aircraft that they were flying.
Of course by this time Japan had military again.
They were an independent nation again, right.
And they also had the F-86s.
And your military assistance group followed them almost just like if you were a commander.
How many airplanes were out of commission because of parts and
And see, we were providing them with parts to maintain their aircraft.
And all their bases, you watched their operational status just like you would if you were commanding them, except you had no authority to tell them what to do.
And you played golf with them.
And you got to know General Ginder, who was on the raid on Pearl Harbor.
Oh really?
No kidding?
Oh yeah.
How was he?
Well, he and I never did get along very good.
I was from SAC.
Well, it was really a fairly interesting job.
It's more of an attache type of job.
That's what it sounds like, personal relations.
Personal relations.
And of course, I was from SAC, so the Japanese always thought that I must be a ball of fire to be selected from SAC to come over and direct them and chief them.
So I got along with them real good.
They were doing a number of things that I changed when I went over there.
Well, of course, the way the Air Force runs it, a generator is not economically repaired because of our labor costs.
I mean, we're paying somebody $8 an hour to repair an electrical generator.
we don't repair it, it's cheaper to buy a new one.
Well, we treated the Japanese exactly the same way, except the Japanese labor was dollar an hour.
So I said, look, I said, General Sanagi, I said, it looks like to me, I'd gone around their bases and located about a million dollars worth of electrical instruments,
airplane instruments, generators, starters.
And I said, look, why don't we just provide you with bits and pieces and you repair them?
Oh, he didn't want to do that because he was getting them for free.
But anyway, I insisted on this.
And I sent it back to Washington as a recommendation.
And we set up an overhaul depot over in Japan to overhaul all these airplane instruments and things of this sort.
And we just found some bits and pieces.
So we saved ourselves a lot of money, but the Japanese didn't like it because it's costing them money to set it up.
But the only way they can become self-sufficient is to
is to do it themselves and also within their labor tolerances.
I mean, they could very easily economically repair these.
But this job is mostly a type of job of helping them get airplanes from off of, get the spare parts from the United States so that we can get the airplanes flying.
And of course I worked on that pretty hard.
And then, well I didn't particularly like that type of game, you had no authority.
I wasn't about a cup of tea, so I worked on a General Burns, who at the time was 5th Air Force Commander, to move out of there.
And there was a schedule to

The Navy commanded the MAG over there, Navy Rear Admiral, and the Air Force had selected a major general to come over to command it, to take his place, so that put two generals in the MAG, so I got out, and I got back to Misawa.
Is it, is this a generalization that has some truth that it was considered back in the 1950s that SAC officers, officers in the Air Force who were in SAC were sort of the cream of the crop?
Oh I don't know.
Well I would say SAC certainly got almost anything they asked for.
I don't know that, I can't say that they got the cream of the crop, but LeMay carried a lot of weight and he had a big mission.
I mean he really had a big mission of keeping the peace and I think that he did a good job.
I thought everybody was scared of him.
Including the Russians.
Yeah, including the Russians.
And I think since then, I think since he left command there, I think SAC has really gone down in its capability of keeping the peace, you might say.
Let's quit for today.
Okay.
We've got 15 minutes before.
